1
00:00:07,040 --> 00:00:09,000
(Ji Chang-wook)

2
00:00:09,960 --> 00:00:12,560
(Won Jin-a)

3
00:00:18,400 --> 00:00:20,280
(Melting Me Softly)

4
00:00:20,360 --> 00:00:22,040
(This program includes
indirect advertisements.)

5
00:00:22,120 --> 00:00:25,120
(All characters, organizations,
places, cases, and incidents)

6
00:00:25,200 --> 00:00:26,920
(in this drama are fictitious.)

7
00:00:27,840 --> 00:00:29,080
Hey, stop acting up.

8
00:00:32,000 --> 00:00:33,680
Did you hear me? Don't act up.

9
00:00:40,560 --> 00:00:42,560
If you keep acting up, I might just

10
00:00:46,640 --> 00:00:47,800
start liking you.

11
00:01:10,200 --> 00:01:12,280
What? What are you looking at?

12
00:01:12,640 --> 00:01:14,720
What is it? Is there something behind me?

13
00:01:14,800 --> 00:01:16,240
What? What are you staring at?

14
00:01:17,400 --> 00:01:21,720
How dare you have the guts
to stare at your senior like that?

15
00:01:23,880 --> 00:01:25,000
Follow me.

16
00:01:26,800 --> 00:01:28,039
Gosh, it's so hot.

17
00:01:29,400 --> 00:01:30,920
Are you going to keep standing there?

18
00:01:31,880 --> 00:01:33,200
I'll just leave on my own.

19
00:01:42,479 --> 00:01:43,560
Here you go.

20
00:01:58,000 --> 00:02:00,840
I was worried that
you might be allergic to strawberries,

21
00:02:01,240 --> 00:02:03,320
chocolate, or kiwi.

22
00:02:04,120 --> 00:02:05,920
So I just got you vanilla ice cream.

23
00:02:07,160 --> 00:02:08,560
I'm not allergic to any of those. But...

24
00:02:09,520 --> 00:02:10,560
But what?

25
00:02:10,639 --> 00:02:12,840
But the only flavor
I don't like is vanilla.

26
00:02:16,040 --> 00:02:17,280
You're unbelievable.

27
00:02:17,360 --> 00:02:19,000
Then give it to me. I'll eat it.

28
00:02:29,560 --> 00:02:31,040
You can give me yours.

29
00:02:32,000 --> 00:02:34,760
I can't give you what I already ate.
I'll just get you a new one.

30
00:02:35,200 --> 00:02:36,920
You're eating what I already ate.

31
00:02:43,600 --> 00:02:44,600
Here.

32
00:02:53,680 --> 00:02:54,760
Are you sober now?

33
00:02:56,120 --> 00:02:57,120
Yes.

34
00:02:59,920 --> 00:03:01,520
Let's get to work. We have a lot to do.

35
00:03:02,360 --> 00:03:04,840
If you drink during working hours
one more time, I'm going to fire you.

36
00:03:06,000 --> 00:03:08,360
-Okay.
-You'd better keep your word.

37
00:03:11,080 --> 00:03:12,640
I have a question.

38
00:03:14,560 --> 00:03:17,400
It's about the bureau chief.

39
00:03:20,079 --> 00:03:23,560
Well, from what I know,

40
00:03:25,440 --> 00:03:27,040
you guys used to date

41
00:03:28,280 --> 00:03:30,400
before you participated
in the cryonics experiment.

42
00:03:33,400 --> 00:03:34,520
Are you guys

43
00:03:35,520 --> 00:03:36,640
still dating?

44
00:03:39,920 --> 00:03:41,360
If you ask me that right now,

45
00:03:41,440 --> 00:03:43,760
wouldn't that affect
our current relationship?

46
00:03:44,360 --> 00:03:46,600
Is that why you're asking me?
I hope that's not why.

47
00:03:47,000 --> 00:03:49,240
I'm only asking because I'm curious.

48
00:03:50,960 --> 00:03:52,000
She and I are not dating.

49
00:03:56,120 --> 00:03:57,160
Don't smile.

50
00:03:59,040 --> 00:04:01,000
Don't say or do anything

51
00:04:01,080 --> 00:04:03,360
that might affect our relationship.

52
00:04:04,280 --> 00:04:06,560
Why not?

53
00:04:06,800 --> 00:04:07,960
Do you really not know why?

54
00:04:08,480 --> 00:04:09,520
No, I don't.

55
00:04:09,640 --> 00:04:12,680
We can't get any closer to each other.

56
00:04:14,400 --> 00:04:17,160
If any one of us approaches
the other person like this...

57
00:04:17,240 --> 00:04:18,240
Yes, that's right.

58
00:04:18,720 --> 00:04:21,120
The other person should take
a step back and maintain a distance.

59
00:04:21,600 --> 00:04:25,240
We should at least stay 50cm,
so 0.5m away from each other.

60
00:04:26,560 --> 00:04:28,000
If we get any closer,

61
00:04:29,760 --> 00:04:30,840
it'll be dangerous for us.

62
00:04:35,720 --> 00:04:37,400
Why does it have to be 0.5m?

63
00:04:42,720 --> 00:04:46,720
(Episode 9:
Between the Cold and the Passion)

64
00:04:47,080 --> 00:04:49,800
I guess you've finally decided to do it.

65
00:04:50,360 --> 00:04:51,400
Yes, that's what I decided.

66
00:04:52,400 --> 00:04:54,480
You and I both knew
it was going to happen one day.

67
00:04:55,200 --> 00:04:58,520
I'm guessing you're here because
you want me to do something for you.

68
00:04:58,880 --> 00:05:01,360
I need the full support
of the News Bureau.

69
00:05:02,400 --> 00:05:05,880
First, let's start off by
announcing that I was the person

70
00:05:05,960 --> 00:05:09,040
who was in charge of planning
the cryonics experiment.

71
00:05:09,120 --> 00:05:11,400
You worked so hard to keep this project
a secret 20 years ago,

72
00:05:11,480 --> 00:05:15,120
but now you want to announce that
you were the one in charge?

73
00:05:15,280 --> 00:05:18,200
The situation has changed.
Things are different now.

74
00:05:19,440 --> 00:05:20,560
Populism.

75
00:05:20,680 --> 00:05:23,000
My party wants me to use that stance

76
00:05:23,080 --> 00:05:24,480
to appeal to the people of this country.

77
00:05:24,760 --> 00:05:26,400
I didn't come up with the idea.

78
00:05:26,680 --> 00:05:27,920
There are

79
00:05:28,440 --> 00:05:31,120
more writers and directors in politics
than in a broadcasting station.

80
00:05:31,640 --> 00:05:34,240
You need to plan everything out
and be strategic.

81
00:05:34,800 --> 00:05:37,680
Do you know why I transferred
to the News Bureau?

82
00:05:39,680 --> 00:05:41,480
Do you remember why I,

83
00:05:41,560 --> 00:05:45,200
a mediocre announcer
who got criticized for her grammar,

84
00:05:46,040 --> 00:05:47,240
volunteered to become a reporter?

85
00:05:48,720 --> 00:05:51,720
It was to find Ma Dong-chan
and do a cover on his disappearance.

86
00:05:51,800 --> 00:05:52,920
That's why I became a reporter.

87
00:05:53,000 --> 00:05:55,720
I had to take a test to become a reporter,
and I did that behind your back--

88
00:05:57,360 --> 00:05:58,920
That's what I did.

89
00:05:59,200 --> 00:06:01,000
And that's how you became

90
00:06:01,200 --> 00:06:03,240
the Chief of the News Bureau.

91
00:06:03,560 --> 00:06:06,320
I couldn't cover anything
whenever that happened.

92
00:06:06,400 --> 00:06:08,800
Because a huge mountain stopped
the huge storm from the front

93
00:06:08,880 --> 00:06:11,040
and the light breeze from the back.

94
00:06:11,120 --> 00:06:13,000
You were such a huge mountain.

95
00:06:13,440 --> 00:06:16,560
Are you sure you can pretend
that you were never such a big mountain?

96
00:06:17,000 --> 00:06:19,480
You wanted to cover up Ma Dong-chan's
disappearance so badly,

97
00:06:19,600 --> 00:06:22,000
but do you think that nobody would
care about it now?

98
00:06:23,840 --> 00:06:25,680
That big mountain

99
00:06:25,760 --> 00:06:27,640
is still... No,

100
00:06:27,960 --> 00:06:30,720
it's even bigger now.

101
00:06:31,000 --> 00:06:33,640
I'm still a mountain that can stop

102
00:06:33,720 --> 00:06:35,280
storms and breezes.

103
00:06:36,600 --> 00:06:39,159
The world has changed, sir.

104
00:06:40,040 --> 00:06:42,680
That's why I'm stepping down
at the perfect timing.

105
00:06:45,560 --> 00:06:49,280
I'm telling you to become
an even bigger mountain.

106
00:06:52,560 --> 00:06:55,920
It's only natural for the chief of news
to become the president.

107
00:06:56,159 --> 00:06:57,680
(Chief of News Bureau, Na Ha-young)

108
00:06:57,760 --> 00:07:01,000
I'll cover all the storms and breezes
for you.

109
00:07:01,320 --> 00:07:03,600
Then you can bring about

110
00:07:03,680 --> 00:07:05,960
a new wind with your title
as the first female president

111
00:07:07,120 --> 00:07:09,040
of a TV network.

112
00:07:11,320 --> 00:07:12,800
President Na Ha-young.

113
00:07:13,840 --> 00:07:15,040
Sounds nice.

114
00:07:28,680 --> 00:07:30,600
(Audition Application)

115
00:07:30,680 --> 00:07:32,920
Gosh, it'll take forever for the writers

116
00:07:33,000 --> 00:07:34,920
to go through the applications.

117
00:07:35,000 --> 00:07:37,320
Gosh, everyone's attention
is on this program

118
00:07:37,400 --> 00:07:38,920
because it's Mr. Ma's show.

119
00:07:39,000 --> 00:07:42,080
Anyway, why haven't
I seen that assistant director

120
00:07:42,159 --> 00:07:43,760
who's apparently an intern?

121
00:07:44,400 --> 00:07:45,720
Where is she?

122
00:07:46,000 --> 00:07:47,920
Do you want to see the applicants?

123
00:07:48,000 --> 00:07:49,400
Sure. Let me see.

124
00:07:51,240 --> 00:07:52,320
Take this.

125
00:07:57,120 --> 00:07:59,240
This is really cool.

126
00:07:59,800 --> 00:08:01,480
The applicants look great, don't they?

127
00:08:01,880 --> 00:08:02,960
Right.

128
00:08:04,760 --> 00:08:07,200
Do you know who our final boss is?

129
00:08:08,000 --> 00:08:09,880
-The president?
-It's this.

130
00:08:10,080 --> 00:08:11,400
This cell phone.

131
00:08:12,560 --> 00:08:15,120
I want to make a program where you
make people live

132
00:08:15,200 --> 00:08:16,600
without their phones for a week

133
00:08:16,680 --> 00:08:19,520
because people these days are all
addicted to them.

134
00:08:19,840 --> 00:08:22,000
And do you know how feeble
people's relationships are?

135
00:08:22,080 --> 00:08:23,560
Most relationships would end

136
00:08:23,640 --> 00:08:26,480
if you took away their phones
and turned off their computers.

137
00:08:26,680 --> 00:08:29,360
And people are also
getting stupider every day.

138
00:08:29,520 --> 00:08:31,040
At this rate, in 100 years,

139
00:08:31,120 --> 00:08:32,679
they'll turn back into homo erectus.

140
00:08:32,760 --> 00:08:34,600
You're right. Come to think of it,

141
00:08:34,679 --> 00:08:36,480
I didn't even memorize
my brother's number.

142
00:08:36,559 --> 00:08:40,640
Right. Ko Nam-tae, 010-349-1974.

143
00:08:42,440 --> 00:08:44,800
Don't think that our relationship
is moving forward with this.

144
00:08:44,960 --> 00:08:48,160
I just memorized
your entire family's numbers

145
00:08:48,240 --> 00:08:50,480
just in case I can't get a hold of you.

146
00:08:51,280 --> 00:08:53,440
I can memorize any set of numbers
once I see them.

147
00:08:53,520 --> 00:08:56,120
I'm sure it's a wonder to you,

148
00:08:56,200 --> 00:08:59,080
but to me, it's just an everyday thing.

149
00:09:00,520 --> 00:09:02,120
Oh, look.

150
00:09:02,360 --> 00:09:05,400
Park Woong-soo, 010-102-8771.

151
00:09:05,680 --> 00:09:08,800
Do you think I memorized his number
because I'm interested in him?

152
00:09:09,920 --> 00:09:11,800
It's all because I'm smart.

153
00:09:14,600 --> 00:09:17,400
Is he overreacting or putting up a wall?

154
00:09:18,080 --> 00:09:20,680
Or is he hitting on me?

155
00:09:22,000 --> 00:09:23,040
(Internship Application)

156
00:09:23,120 --> 00:09:26,160
These are the applicants who made it
through three screenings.

157
00:09:26,240 --> 00:09:28,480
Let's put two in each team.

158
00:09:29,240 --> 00:09:31,480
This is an opportunity
to save the Variety Department.

159
00:09:31,640 --> 00:09:32,960
We're getting a hold of

160
00:09:33,040 --> 00:09:34,840
future talents in advance.

161
00:09:34,920 --> 00:09:37,720
But all of those interns said
they want to work

162
00:09:37,800 --> 00:09:39,480
with Director Ma Dong-chan.

163
00:09:39,560 --> 00:09:41,200
It's because they never worked with him.

164
00:09:41,280 --> 00:09:43,800
You have no idea how much he harasses you.
My gosh!

165
00:09:48,200 --> 00:09:50,200
Did you turn in the budget?

166
00:09:50,280 --> 00:09:51,680
I was about to.

167
00:09:51,760 --> 00:09:52,880
Is that so?

168
00:09:52,960 --> 00:09:54,680
Why don't you do it in a month?

169
00:09:54,840 --> 00:09:56,640
I told you to do it ages ago.

170
00:09:56,720 --> 00:09:57,840
Okay.

171
00:09:58,400 --> 00:10:00,080
-Hyun-gi.
-Yes?

172
00:10:00,760 --> 00:10:02,560
Yes, what?

173
00:10:02,640 --> 00:10:04,240
How long will you stay here?

174
00:10:04,440 --> 00:10:06,520
You need to move your office next to mine.

175
00:10:07,640 --> 00:10:08,880
Move out.

176
00:10:13,760 --> 00:10:14,880
"Move out"?

177
00:10:14,960 --> 00:10:16,600
I've never even been told that
by my landlords.

178
00:10:23,800 --> 00:10:25,200
What is this?

179
00:10:25,800 --> 00:10:28,440
He's so unpredictable,
playing with my heart.

180
00:10:29,280 --> 00:10:30,920
"I might just start liking you."

181
00:10:31,000 --> 00:10:33,480
But then what was that about the 0.5m?

182
00:10:35,000 --> 00:10:36,880
My gosh.

183
00:10:37,160 --> 00:10:38,840
I won't let him walk all over me.

184
00:11:09,840 --> 00:11:11,480
Make sure you don't get caught.

185
00:11:15,080 --> 00:11:17,240
No one else should find out

186
00:11:17,320 --> 00:11:19,640
what your story is, right?

187
00:11:21,800 --> 00:11:23,640
I don't want Dong-chan

188
00:11:24,920 --> 00:11:26,600
to get into trouble.

189
00:11:49,560 --> 00:11:51,640
The intern must have amazing connections.

190
00:11:53,320 --> 00:11:55,320
All she did was text me, the main writer,

191
00:11:55,400 --> 00:11:57,200
and she never came by to greet me.

192
00:11:58,400 --> 00:12:00,440
Where has she been all day?

193
00:12:05,600 --> 00:12:07,080
I need to speak with you.

194
00:12:11,720 --> 00:12:13,240
Did you say hi to the writer?

195
00:12:13,320 --> 00:12:15,200
I sent her a text message.

196
00:12:15,360 --> 00:12:17,720
I thought it would be rude
to call her immediately.

197
00:12:17,800 --> 00:12:19,680
She doesn't think so.

198
00:12:19,760 --> 00:12:21,880
She doesn't think texting
is a way of communicating.

199
00:12:21,960 --> 00:12:24,200
She only acknowledges
in-person conversations.

200
00:12:24,280 --> 00:12:25,520
You got on her bad side.

201
00:12:25,720 --> 00:12:26,720
What should I do?

202
00:12:26,800 --> 00:12:28,720
What do you think? You'll be bullied.

203
00:12:29,000 --> 00:12:31,920
She looks mean, but she's even meaner.

204
00:12:32,080 --> 00:12:33,520
I'm sure she has

205
00:12:33,600 --> 00:12:35,120
some trouble with her autonomic nerves.

206
00:12:35,200 --> 00:12:36,320
Even I get scared of her.

207
00:12:36,400 --> 00:12:39,320
But why do you want to work
with a writer like her?

208
00:12:39,400 --> 00:12:41,880
She writes great scripts,
gets good guests, and plans well.

209
00:12:42,000 --> 00:12:43,080
I just need her to do her job.

210
00:12:43,160 --> 00:12:44,480
It's not like I'm going to date her.

211
00:12:44,560 --> 00:12:46,320
I'll try to get along with her.

212
00:12:46,600 --> 00:12:48,320
I'm good at moving people's hearts.

213
00:12:48,920 --> 00:12:51,160
I know that about you.

214
00:12:57,000 --> 00:12:59,560
Oh, she's apparently a huge fan of BTS.

215
00:12:59,640 --> 00:13:01,720
You better study about them.

216
00:13:01,800 --> 00:13:03,480
If you stammer because
you don't know them,

217
00:13:03,560 --> 00:13:04,960
you'll end up being sent somewhere

218
00:13:05,040 --> 00:13:07,440
out in the universe
where I can't help you.

219
00:13:07,520 --> 00:13:09,200
"Goodbye, Ko Mi-ran." Like this.

220
00:13:09,520 --> 00:13:11,320
BTS?

221
00:13:12,760 --> 00:13:14,160
Who is that?

222
00:13:18,360 --> 00:13:21,760
Right. The way you said that
and the way you looked

223
00:13:22,400 --> 00:13:23,640
will make her beat you.

224
00:13:34,080 --> 00:13:35,800
We're working overtime tonight.

225
00:13:44,120 --> 00:13:45,760
Kim Nam-joon, Kim Seok-jin,

226
00:13:45,840 --> 00:13:48,040
Min Yoon-gi, Jung Ho-seok,

227
00:13:48,160 --> 00:13:49,520
Park Ji-min,

228
00:13:49,840 --> 00:13:52,320
Kim Tae-hyung, Jeon Jung-kook, BTS.

229
00:13:52,640 --> 00:13:54,400
Other than those people in their 40s,

230
00:13:54,480 --> 00:13:56,400
we need to get some celebrities here too.

231
00:13:56,560 --> 00:13:57,840
Did you make a list of candidates?

232
00:13:57,920 --> 00:14:01,080
I plan on sending out the proposal
to management agencies

233
00:14:01,160 --> 00:14:03,040
and get the singers' schedules.

234
00:14:03,160 --> 00:14:05,400
Let's get BTS here.

235
00:14:07,840 --> 00:14:09,520
Kim Nam-joon, Kim Seok-jin, Min Yoon-gi,

236
00:14:09,600 --> 00:14:11,880
Jung Ho-seok, Park Ji-min,
Kim Tae-hyung, Jeon Jung-kook.

237
00:14:11,960 --> 00:14:13,160
Let's get all of them.

238
00:14:13,640 --> 00:14:15,520
Are you kidding me, Intern?

239
00:14:15,800 --> 00:14:17,200
I'm not joking.

240
00:14:17,320 --> 00:14:19,200
I really love BTS too.

241
00:14:19,280 --> 00:14:20,520
Should we get them?

242
00:14:21,680 --> 00:14:23,520
BTS isn't in Korea right now.

243
00:14:23,600 --> 00:14:24,760
But...

244
00:14:33,360 --> 00:14:34,880
Mi-ran loves

245
00:14:35,120 --> 00:14:37,240
this program a little too much.

246
00:14:37,920 --> 00:14:39,920
I know BTS is a global star,

247
00:14:40,000 --> 00:14:41,640
but we can try to get them.

248
00:14:42,960 --> 00:14:44,800
Why are you all so shocked?

249
00:14:45,200 --> 00:14:47,720
Well, because of our budget...
We can make a call.

250
00:14:47,800 --> 00:14:49,320
-Yes.
-We can try.

251
00:14:49,400 --> 00:14:51,520
It doesn't cost anything to make a call.

252
00:14:51,600 --> 00:14:53,640
-Let's ask them.
-What's their number?

253
00:14:53,720 --> 00:14:55,560
I'm sure their agency will pick up.

254
00:14:55,640 --> 00:14:57,600
Are there any other celebrities?

255
00:14:57,680 --> 00:14:59,480
Kwak Cheol-yong.

256
00:14:59,560 --> 00:15:01,400
Kwak Cheol-yong? What's his name...

257
00:15:01,480 --> 00:15:03,400
-I mean, give me the info.
-Yes, him.

258
00:15:03,480 --> 00:15:04,560
Will you call them?

259
00:15:07,560 --> 00:15:09,440
(Chairman Lee Seok-du of Unsung Group)

260
00:15:10,560 --> 00:15:11,920
(Restricted Number)

261
00:15:16,120 --> 00:15:17,080
Hello?

262
00:15:17,160 --> 00:15:20,000
